<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-271-058  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 271 058.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  May 15 1989 v8 n10 p45(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Pub. Co. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>$22.5M buy gets fiber-optic cable readied for battle.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Green, Robert.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   American Telephone and Telegraph Co. (contracts).andO;Ticker:    T.andO;Topic:     United States. Army. Communications-Electronics CommandFiber OpticsGovernment ContractsCommunications EquipmentCables.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>$22.5M Buy Gets Fiber-Optic Cable Readied for BattleandM;The Army Communications Electronics Command (CECOM) recently awarded ATandamp;T Co.andO;a $22.5 million contract for tactical fiber-optic cable under an agreementthat will make the company's so-called &quot;long haul&quot; assemblies the standardfor the Air Force and the Marines as well.andM;The Fiber Optic Transmission System (FOTS) is based on ruggedized cable thatcan extend up to 8 kilometers.andP;  It will be used principally by the Army tolink battlefield communications shelters.andM;A CECOM official described the shelters as &quot;similar to telephone companyswitching centers.&quot;andP;  He said the cables also are used in headquarters localarea networks and will replace radio devices in the remote firing of Patriotsurface-to-air missiles.andM;The cables provide the advantage of emitting none of the telltale signalscommon to radio-controlled systems, which can be intercepted by a potentialenemy and give away missile location, he said.andM;Bill Womack, ATandamp;T FOTS program manager, said the fiber-optic lines willreplace current metallic or dual-coaxial cable the Army has been using tolink shelters.andP;  It will not be fielded for about two years, pendingdevelopment of electro-optical communications devices under a separate Armyprocurement.andM;That contract was awarded last year to FiberCom Inc. of Roanoke, Va.andP;  Thecompany will deliver what an Army spokesman described as &quot;essentially anoptical modem that changes an electrical signal to a light-emitting diode.&quot;andM;&quot;ATandamp;T got involved in this program through an Randamp;D contract we won in 1984 todevelop tactical fiber-optic cable,&quot; Womack said.andP;  &quot;Our approach was to buildon the current commercial technology.&quot;andM;Womack said ATandamp;T's standard biconic connector, a sleeve-type fixture, wasmodified for military use.andP;  The metallic and dual-coaxial cable in userequires repeaters every quarter mile to boost the signal, Womack said.andP;  ButFOTS works without repeaters and is more mobile.andO;</TEXT></DOC>